ChIP-seq Analysis¶

The analysis below studies the binnding sites of COUP-TFII also refered as NR2F2. The data was collected from GEO https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/geo/query/acc.cgi?acc=GSE52008. ChIP-seq was performed on human endometrial stromal cells (HESC) treated with deciduogenic hormones using an antibody against COUP-TFII. As input, inmunoprecipitation with normal rabbit IgG was performed.

Biological system¶

https://www.cell.com/cancer-cell/fulltext/S1535-6108(18)30127-2#figures

Precise control of inflammation plays a very important role in maintaining a well-balanced immune response and preventing a persistent state of inflammation. The nuclear factor erythroid 2-like 2 (NRF2) also know as Chicken ovalbumin upstream promoter-transcription factor II (COUP-TFII) serves as a key mediator in controlling inflammation [1]. When stabilized due to oxidative stress, NRF2 triggers the expression of antioxidants and genes that protect cells, leading to an anti-inflammatory effect essential for the body's healing process [2]. As we known, overactivation or underactivation of NRF2 is involved in the development of chronic diseases due to its important role regulating inflamatory responses.

NRF2 operates by binding to specific sequences known as AREs (antioxidant response elements) in the DNA of cells, as shown in the figure above [2]. These AREs are regions in the DNA that regulates the transcription of genes responsible for antioxidants and detoxification enzymes [2]. The activation of these genes helps the cell combat oxidative stress, maintain redox balance, and defend against harmful molecules known as reactive oxygen species [2]. Furthermore, it is known that NRF2 is involved in some of the following processes: cell-fate specification, organogenesis, angiogenesis and metabolism [1].

Some studies have studied the role of this transcription factor in the female reproduction by studying mice but its role in humans remains unknown that is why the autors of this experiment decided to studied it [1]. The role of NRF2 in the uterous may give us insight to better understand Endometriosis, a very common desease affecting women. This is characterize by chronic pelvic pain and it is associated with progesteron insensitivity (result from the deregulation of the progesterone receptor, steroid receptor coactivators etc). Prevous studies found that mice lacking NRF2, down-regulate stromal progesterone receptors. This may suggest that this transcription factor plays an important role in progesterone resistance in women with the disease [1]. In fact, in the same study [1], after doing a differential expression analysis, they found that NRF2 is highly expressed in endometrial stoma of healthy women while the expression is reduced in women with endometriosis [1]. Due to this, it is of great interest to know more about the interaction of this transcription factor with the DNA by chIP-seq analysis.

Experiment design¶

Pooled primary human endometrial stromal cells from 6 healthy women upon decidualization with a hormone cocktail of cAMP, E2 and medroxyprogesterone acetate where analysed in the presence of antibodies for COUP-TFII (N2RF2). The data set of this study consists of two samples, as shown in the following image.

ChIP-seq details¶

The experiment was done using Illumina Genome Analyzer II to obtain the sequencing results. Single reads were obtained.

Downloading the sample containing the antibody and QC Quality control¶

First, the sample containing the antibody was analyzed. The following code lines do:

  • Download the reads in a fastq format
  • Quality assessment using fastqc command

Peak Visualization with IGV¶














IGV one of the detected peaks was visualized. The peak is located in the IGF1R gene. This gene is a target gene of the COUP-TFII transcription factor and is associated with focal adhesion [1]. This is a good sign of data quality.
It can be seen the difference in the number of reads between the positive sample and the control (input sample). In purple we can see the coverage of the positive sample. The reads in both samples were colored by strand (red and blue colors). As a quality control measure it is observed that in the peak the number of blue and red reads is similar.






























Peak calling using MACS2¶














In order to identify the true peaks in the analysis one of the tools available for these is macs2. As inputs it takes the sorted bam files of the positive and control samples. A p-value of 1e-10 was specified. Although this value is pretty strict, it was implemented given a high number of detected peaks with higher p-values. Using such a small p-value suggests that the identified peaks are likely to be biologically meaningful and not just random noise or background signal. Also, this was the p-value implemented in the reference study [1].


A total of 10364 peaks were identified, given that this number is very high the number of peaks was reduced to the 3000 most significant ones. From the narrowPeaks file the bed file was obtained.













In [78]:



    


export OMP_NUM_THREADS=20
macs2 callpeak -t SRR1023110.sorted.bam -c SRR1023111.sorted.bam -n NR2F2 -g hs -p 1e-10

The novo Motifs analysis¶














First, the bed file containing the peaks selected in the step above is converted to a fasta file using bedtools getfasta command. RSAT software is going to be used search for motifs according to the input peaks. HOMOMOCO database was selected for human transcription factors. 
The results from RSAT can be seen in the following link: https://jupyter.gbiomed.kuleuven.be/user/r0870275/view/Chip-seq/peak-motifs_synthesis.html


The first hit corresponds to NRF2 (COT2) motif, this corresponds to the NRF2 motif, as expected! The significance is very high.


From the 3000 peaks selected 25% (758 direct peaks) of these contain this motif. This number is lower than expected but can be due to the fact that the totality of the peaks is not being used, and that only the higer 3000 peaks were selected.


The AAAGGTCA motif found by RSAT correspond to the exact motif found by the reference study [1].

PWM and track enrichment¶














the results of this analysis are found in the following link: https://gbiomed.kuleuven.be/apps/lcb/i-cisTarget/reports/9aed76dddef72a72064049e591f8b623c4ad01ca/report.html


Try this link if the other does not work: https://jupyter.gbiomed.kuleuven.be/user/r0870275/view/Chip-seq/i-cisTarget_%20results%20for%20chip.html




























































The first hits do not correspond to the NRF2 (COT2) motif. Although it was found further down (figure above). This could have happen given the characteristics of the TF studied. It is also important to mencioned that according to the refence study [1], NRF2 is considered an orphan TF. this, makes more dificult to perform an PWD analysis given that the binding usually is context-dependent. This means that their binding motifs and regulatory functions depend on celular conditions or specific cell types (endometrial stromal cells, in our case).


Given that the results from this where not as good as expected, only the peaks from the de novo motif discovery are going to be taken into account.















Linking the results peaks to genes¶














In GREAT webpage, we tested first with the complete peaks and then with the enriched peaks after the de novo motif discovery, the finals results showed here are using the enriched peaks only. We can see in the figure below that some pathways enriched were integrin signalling, angiogenesis,  VEGF signaling, focal adhesion, cytokine-cytokine receptor interaction, etc.













































This results are similar to the pathways found by the authors of the data. As observed in the table below from the published paper based on the ChIP-seq data.






























This are some of the genes for the cytokine-cytokine receptor interaction pathway.






























A .txt file containing all the genes linked to the peaks was downloaded and uploaded to the current working directory. The name of the file is 20231205-public-3.0.0-rK5X2b-hg19-all-gene.txt















As a data quality check, we found that the gene IGF1R is included, this is a good sign! since we knew from before that we had a peak on this gene when we were visualizing the peaks in IGV.

Conclusions¶














The results of ChIP-seq analysis of the TF NRF2 (COUP-TFII) showed that this transcription factor act by directly binding to genes involved in pathways like integrin signalling, VEGF signaling, focal adhesion and cytokine-cytokine receptor interaction. These are related in general to cell adhesion, angiogenesis and inflamation which are hallmarks of endometriosis [1]. This confirms that the transcription factor studied here is involved with the development of the disease. The direct target genes identified by this analysis were also found in the related study [1].
